Task: 2025-12-15__AUTH-SYSTEM
Owner: Tech Lead Agent (proposal only; requires human approval)
Status: Draft for review

## 1) Goals & Scope (In-Task)
- NextAuth-based auth with email/password + Google + Apple.
- Email verification (single-use, time-bound), password reset.
- Age verification gate via Veriff (per PM decision), with clear states and gating.
- Session and sign-out hygiene; account states enforced across app.
- Compliant handling of secrets, tokens, and PII per CODEBASE_ARCHITECTURE_RULES.

## 2) Assumptions & Dependencies
- Email delivery provider + DNS (SPF/DKIM) available.
- OAuth creds provisioned (Google, Apple).
- Veriff approved for adult-content use; API keys available.
- No MFA/2FA in this phase; no mobile-specific UX.
- pnpm only (CODEBASE_GOVERNANCE_RULES); NextAuth already aligned with stack.

## 3) Domain Model & States (conceptual, schema changes to be designed in engineering)
- User core: id, email (unique), emailVerifiedAt, passwordHash (nullable for social-only), providerLinks [{provider, providerUserId, emailVerified}].
- AccountState: `email_unverified`, `age_pending`, `age_denied`, `active`, `locked`.
- AgeVerification: id, userId, providerSessionId, status (`pending|passed|failed|needs_review`), method, country, livenessScore?, fraudScore?, verifiedAt?, failureReason?, expiresAt?, metadata JSON, audit timestamps.
- VerificationToken: id, userId, type (`email_verify|password_reset`), tokenHash (hashed), expiresAt, consumedAt, createdAt, createdIp.
- Session: NextAuth session store (DB-backed) with rotation and absolute/idle timeouts; store accountState + age status snapshot for quick gating.

## 4) Layered Architecture (per CODEBASE_ARCHITECTURE_RULES)
- Routes (`app/api/**/route.ts`): thin; map HTTP → controller.
- Controllers (`src/app/api/_controllers/authController.ts` etc.): orchestrate validation, call services, shape responses.
- Services (`src/services/authService.ts`, `ageVerificationService.ts`, `emailService.ts`): business logic, token issuance/validation, state transitions, provider orchestration.
- Repositories (`src/repositories/userRepository.ts`, `tokenRepository.ts`, `ageVerificationRepository.ts`): DB access via Prisma; no business rules.
- Provider client (`src/services/providers/veriffClient.ts`): wraps Veriff REST/Webhooks; no domain logic.
- Middleware: rate limiting, auth/session extraction, state gating; no duplication in routes.

## 5) Flows (happy path + key branches)
- Email signup: create user (email lowercase, unique); hash password (argon2/bcrypt); issue email verification token; send email; user state = `email_unverified`.
- Email verification: validate token (hash, expiry, single-use); set emailVerifiedAt; if age verification required, move to `age_pending`; else `active`.
- Login email/password: verify credentials; enforce lockout policy; deny if state `locked`; if `email_unverified` allow limited session (gated) but block restricted areas; apply session rotation.
- Social login (Google/Apple): NextAuth provider; if verified email matches existing verified user → link provider; if email exists but unverified → require verify; if Apple relay non-verified → prompt add primary email post-login; prevent duplicate accounts.
- Password reset: request creates reset token (single-use, time-bound, rate limited); email generic confirmation; redeem sets new password, clears sessions, rotates tokens.
- Age verification (Veriff): initiate session via service; store providerSessionId/status `pending`; webhook or polling updates status; on `passed` → state `active`; on `failed` → `age_denied`; support retry count; purge sensitive artifacts per retention policy.
- Sign-out: invalidate session server-side; ensure token rotation on subsequent sign-in.

## 6) HTTP/API & Routing Plan (Next.js App Router)
- `app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts`: NextAuth handler configured for credentials + Google + Apple; adapters point to repositories; callbacks enforce state gating.
- `app/api/auth/email/verify/route.ts`: accept token; call controller→service to consume token and update state.
- `app/api/auth/password/reset/request/route.ts`: request reset token.
- `app/api/auth/password/reset/confirm/route.ts`: consume token, set new password, revoke sessions.
- `app/api/age/verify/initiate/route.ts`: start Veriff session; returns client token/url.
- `app/api/age/verify/webhook/route.ts`: receive Veriff webhooks; signature validation; update status; audit log.
- Middleware: rate limiting and auth gating for sensitive routes; feature flags optional for rollout.

## 7) Session & Security Policies
- Password policy (per PM): min 12 chars, upper+lower+digit+symbol; check against breached list (HIBP k-anon); prevent recent reuse.
- Session lifetime: idle 12h, absolute 30d, “keep me signed in” respects absolute cap; rotate on sign-in and every 12h.
- Lockout & rate limits: login/register/reset/verify-resend all rate-limited; account lock after repeated failures with cool-off.
- Token handling: store hashed tokens with expiry; single-use; include IP/user-agent in audit.
- Secrets: all credentials via env; no secrets in repo; `.env.example` updated by engineering.
- PII minimization: store only necessary Veriff metadata; purge docs/biometrics within 30 days; retain audit status/timestamps.
- Email responses: generic messaging to avoid account enumeration.

## 8) Data & Schema Changes (to be detailed by engineering, no migrations here)
- New tables/fields likely: users (state, emailVerifiedAt, passwordHash nullable), providerLinks, verification_tokens, age_verifications, sessions (if DB-backed adapter), audit logs (minimal).
- Indices: email unique, providerUserId scoped to provider, tokenHash indexed, age_verifications userId index.
- Soft-delete not required here; locked state instead.

## 9) Provider Integration (Veriff)
- Client wrapper handles: session creation, status polling (if needed), webhook signature verification, error normalization, retry with backoff.
- Configurable policies: allowed methods (document + selfie), country allowlist/denylist (config), max retries, SLA timeouts.
- Webhook security: HMAC verification, idempotent updates (based on providerSessionId + status).

## 10) Observability & Audit
- Log auth events (register, login, reset request/confirm, verify, age status changes) with userId, result, reason, IP/UA (hashed UA acceptable), no sensitive payloads.
- Metrics: rate-limit hits, verification success/failure, reset success, provider latency.
- Audit trail for age verification decisions (status, timestamp, provider ref).

## 11) Frontend Contract (non-UI-detailed)
- Forms/pages: signup, login, verify-email state page, resend verification, request reset, reset password, age verification start/status page, error states.
- States to surface: email sent, verified, expired link, reset sent, reset success, age pending, age failed (retry), age verified, locked.
- API surface: use single API client; no inline fetch in components; containers handle data, UI components remain dumb per architecture rules.

## 12) Testing Strategy (for engineering)
- Unit: services (auth, token, age verification), password policy, token expiry, state transitions.
- Integration: NextAuth callbacks, repository + service interactions, webhook handling, rate limiting behavior.
- E2E (happy + edge): signup + verify, social login linking, reset flow, age verification pass/fail, locked account behavior, session rotation.
- Security tests: replay of tokens, enumeration resilience, webhook signature failure.

## 13) Risks & Mitigations
- OAuth/Veriff credential delays → block: mitigate by feature flag + fallbacks for email-only until ready (if approved).
- Email deliverability → block verification/reset: mitigate SPF/DKIM, bounce monitoring, resend with rate limits.
- False negatives in age check: allow retry; log for appeal; keep manual review hook (future).
- Apple private relay loss: prompt user to add primary email post-signup; store contact update reminder.

## 14) Out of Scope (confirmed)
- MFA/2FA, phone/SMS OTP, admin review tools, mobile-specific UX, payouts/KYC, domain-specific UI polish beyond required forms.

## 15) Approvals Needed
- Human approval of this architecture before engineering or agent execution (FE/BE/DevOps).
